<!DOCTYPE html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="utf-8" /><title>Forms: checkboxes and radio buttons</title><style type="text/css">/*** page styling ***/body {	color: #666666;	font-family: georgia, serif;	}	code {	color: #444;	font-weight: bold;	font-size: 1.1em;}li {margin-bottom: .5em;}/*** form styling goes here ***/form {	border-radius: 10px;	-webkit-border-radius: 10px;	-moz-border-radius: 10px;	padding: 8px;	background-color: #dfdfdf;	width: 500px;	}fieldset {	padding: 10px;	background-color: #dfdfdf;	border-bottom:1px dotted #808080;	border-right: 0;	border-left:0;	border-top:0;	}label {	font-family: helvetica, sans-serif;	font-size: .7em;}label.text-input {	display: block;	float: left;	width: 150px;	}	label.text-area {	display: block;}label.checkbox {	display: block;	float: left;	width: 100px;	margin-left: 30px;	}input[type="checkbox"] {	margin-left: -130px; /* this, with the checkbox label's left margin of 30 and width of 100, gets the checkbox displaying first even though it comes after the label in the code */}label.radio {	display: block;	float: left;	width: 100px;	margin-left: 30px;	}input[type="radio"] {	margin-left: -130px;}input.submit {	border-radius:10px;	background-color: #fff;	}h4 {	font-weight: normal;}legend {	font-weight: bold;	font-size: 1em;	padding-bottom: 5px;}</style></head><body><header><h1>Writing a form with checkboxes and radio buttons</h1></header><article><h2>Writing a form and using a script to process the input</h2><p>Write a simple form that can take user input and process it. You'll need the following <code>form</code> elements:</p><ul><li>The <code>form</code> itself. Don't forget the required <code>method</code> and <code>action</code> attributes. The <code>action</code> needs to connect to the script you'll write on <code>form-script.php</code>.</li><li>Begin with a hidden input field that sends the time that the form was submitted. You'll put the php script inside the value for the <code>value</code> attribute. Working with dates/times in MySQL can be a challenge, so we'll use the php date/time information and store it as a string (ie: can't be used to make calculations, but can be used in a display of day, date and/or time). </li><li>You'll have 4 sections to the form: Contact Information, Favorite Things, Comments and Submit Your Form. Use <code>fieldset</code> with its <code>legend</code> to separate the three sections.</li><li>In Contact Information, get the user's First Name, Last Name and email. You'll use <code>input</code> fields for these. Remember the proper <code>type</code>, <code>name</code> and <code>id</code> attributes attributes for input elements. </li><li>In Favorite Things, you'll have two sets of input: Favorite Color and TV Shows. Use <code>radio</code> input for the favorite color (you only have one definitionally), and checkboxes for TV shows.  Create your own choices for each one, but they all must have at least 4 choices. The form screenshot can help you with the content you need to put in.</li><li>In Comments, use a <code>textarea</code> so the user can input some text. Use <code>name</code>, <code>id</code>, <code>cols</code> and <code>rows</code> attributes.</li><li>For your input and textareas, use <code>label</code> to label them. This is an important usability feature. Labels come *before* the input and text areas so that assistive technologies read them in a logical way for people who cannot see them. In addition to that, use the <code>for</code> attribute in each label and be sure it matches the name/id of the field.</li><li>Use a <code>submit</code> type of <code>input</code> in the last fieldset so the form can be submitted. This is what allows the form to send the data to the script you've specified in the <code>action</code> attribute. The special submit input field can take the <code>value</code> attribute to customize the text on the button itself. Keep it simple.</li></ul></article><!-- write your form here. you'll need to add some class styles to the form because the label element needs to be distinguished. see the styled form from the class exercises for hints on markup and styling. --> <form id="miniproject" name="miniproject" method="post" action="miniproject-script.php"><input type="hidden" name="time" id="time" value="<?php echo date('h:i:s A') ?>" /><fieldset><legend>Personal Information</legend><label class="text-input" for="fname">First Name</label><input type="text" name="fname" id="fname" /><br /><label class="text-input" for="lname">Last Name</label><input type="text" name="lname" id="lname" /><br /><label class="text-input" for="email">Email</label><input type="text" name="email" id="email" /><br /></fieldset><fieldset><legend>Favorite Things</legend><h4>Favorite Color</h4><label class="radio" for="blue">blue</label><input type="radio" name="color[ ]" id="blue" value="blue" /><br /><label class="radio" for="red">red</label><input type="radio" name="color[ ]" id="red" value="red" /><br /><label class="radio" for="yellow">yellow</label><input type="radio" name="color[ ]" id="yellow" value="yellow" /><br /><label class="radio" for="purple">purple</label><input type="radio" name="color[ ]" id="purple" value="purple" /><br /><h4>TV Shows<br />Have you watched any of these shows? Choose all that apply</h4><label class="checkbox" for="simpsons">The Simpsons</label><input type="checkbox" name="tv[ ]" id="simpsons" value="The Simpsons" /><br /><label class="checkbox" for="friends">Friends</label><input type="checkbox" name="tv[ ]" id="friends" value="Friends" /><br /><label class="checkbox" for="mash">MASH</label><input type="checkbox" name="tv[ ]" id="mash" value="Mash" /><br /><label class="checkbox" for="cheers">Cheers</label><input type="checkbox" name="tv[ ]" id="cheers" value="Cheers" /></fieldset><fieldset><legend>Comments</legend><label class="text-area" for="comments">Comments</label><textarea name="comments" cols="65" rows="10"></textarea><br /></fieldset><fieldset>	<legend>Submit Your Form</legend><input type="submit" id="submitbutton" value="Submit your form" class="submit" /></fieldset></form></body></html>